当たり前だけど1番上手い笑

あなたは素晴らしい創造神です
私が特に好きなTWICEの曲の振り付けを全部あなたがしてくれました。何度も動画を再生しました。「良い音楽で1度、素晴らしいパフォーマンスで2度魅了させる」グループにふさわしい振り付け師さんです。
作詞者や作曲者が歌を提供したアイドルと歌ったり伴奏するコラボが大好きな私にとってこれほど嬉しい動画はありません、本当にありがとうございます

author: @johns5558
text:
Womens coreography is often chosen because the way their proportions trigger the symmetries as perceived by the eye.

Men can either chose to do the choreo with the inflections and shapes of the native movement or adjust the choreo for the way male body proportions  wil form the patterns on the eye,   This is particularly apparent across the shoulders and chest and the hips - where males and females differ the most by way of ratio to other body measurements. He often needs to squeeze smaller on movements focused there and - in particular - thats where Id preferred to see reinterpretation. 

While one can say that either is judgement / bias / traditional interpretation etc, I personally would preferred to see men favour the masculine reinterpretation of the original movement in accord with the natural state of the male body. This is even more true for western men who by way of statistical proportion are by height even taller than their Asian counterparts. (JYP can sometimes pull off and emulate female movements without great body deformation)

Even here, you see he tends to rip it when not forced to emulate the original movement or when the movement is natively male compatible. 1:23 emphasises hips, which for a male can become a deformation pattern. 1:19 the movement is unisex shoulders and he rips it.

Thoughts
